<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900711-0052</DOCNO><DOCID>900711-0052.</DOCID><HL>   FDIC Said to Mull   Filing Civil Charges   Against Neil Bush</HL><DATE>07/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. isconsidering filing civil charges against President Bush's sonNeil and other former officials of a Colorado thrift, but afinal decision hasn't been made yet, an agency spokesmansaid.   Neil Bush, a Denver oil businessman, was an outsidedirector of Silverado Banking Savings andamp; Loan Association,which failed in late 1988 at an expected cost to thegovernment of $1 billion. The Office of Thrift Supervisionhas charged him in an administrative action with violatingconflict-of-interest rules as a Silverado director. Mr. Bushhas denied any wrongdoing.</LP><TEXT>   The FDIC routinely files civil charges against directorsand officers of failed institutions, as well as outsideattorneys and accountants, in cases where the government bankand thrift insurance funds suffer a loss. The agencytypically brings charges of negligence and breach offiduciary duty to the institution, seeking to cover itslosses. Banks and thrifts usually carry insurance for theirofficers and directors to protect them from such suits.   ABC News reported last night that the FDIC is about tofile a $200 million civil suit against Mr. Bush and otherformer Silverado officials, but the FDIC spokesman, said &quot;nofinal decision&quot; has been made on whether to bring a suit.High-level officials at the FDIC confirmed that a finaldecision hasn't been made, but one person said a decision&quot;isn't too far off.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>